%N A096370 a(n) is one greater than the number of repeated applications of the Reverse and Add (RA) transform applied to the binary representation of n that are required to reach a palindrome, or a(n)=0 if a palindrome is never reached.
%e A096370 For n=20, we have 20=10100 (base 2) and
%e A096370 (RA^0)10100=10100
%e A096370 (RA^1)10100=11001
%e A096370 (RA^2)10100=101100
%e A096370 (RA^3)10100=111001
%e A096370 (RA^4)10100=1100000
%e A096370 (RA^5)10100=1100011 (a palindrome).
%e A096370 Thus a(20)=5+1=6.
%e A096370 For n=22, we get
%e A096370 (RA^9)=> 1101000101
%e A096370 (RA^13)=> 110010001101
%e A096370 (RA^17)=> 11000100011101
%e A096370 (RA^21)=> 1100001000111101
%e A096370 (RA^25)=>110000010001111101
%e A096370 (RA^(4k+1)=>1^2 0^(k-1) 1 0^3 1^(k-1) 0 1, where here 0^k denotes 000...0 (k times). A regular pattern also occurs for the intermediate values, showing that a palindrome never occurs. Thus a(22)=0.
